 # Spike: limit unbuffer-relay wrapping to pipeline head only
 
-
+Currently, every wrapped external command goes through unbuffer-relay independently. In a pipeline like `jj log | grep foo | head`, all three commands get individual PTY wrappers. Only the head of the pipeline needs the PTY (for isatty(stdout) color preservation) — downstream commands receive piped input regardless.
+
+Possible approaches to investigate:
+1. Use `commandline` tokenization in fish_preexec to parse the pipeline, and only wrap the first command. Unwrap downstream commands by calling `command <original>` directly. Unknown: does `commandline` parse pipelines? Does `command` work correctly mid-pipeline in this context?
+2. Undefine wrappers in fish_postexec and recreate in fish_preexec, choosing per-position wrapping. Unknown: overhead of constant create/delete cycles.
+3. Have the wrapper function itself detect if it's in a pipeline (check if stdout is a pipe) and skip unbuffer-relay if so. This might be the simplest — `test -t 1` returns false when stdout is a pipe.
+
+Low priority unless we measure that chained unbuffer-relay calls cause latency or behavioral issues.
